# App Store Scraper – Project Standards

- **Stack**: TypeScript (ESM), Node ≥20, Vitest, Zod, tsup. Use `src/lib/*.ts` for core logic; types in `src/types/`.
- **Documentation**: When adding or updating code, create or update the code documentation that goes along with it (JSDoc for public APIs, README/CHANGELOG if user-facing).
- **External data**: Validate all API/HTML responses with Zod schemas from `src/lib/schemas.ts`. Prefer `safeParse` and throw clear errors on failure.
- **Security**: Do not interpolate user/options (e.g. `country`, `collection`, `category`, `sort`) into URLs without validating against allowlists (e.g. `markets`, `Collection`, `Category`). See `docs/CODE-REVIEW.md` for details.
- **Design decisions**: For non-obvious choices (e.g. API vs scraping, token handling), check `docs/DEV-DECISIONS.md` and keep it updated when making or reversing such decisions.
- **Postponed work**: Before implementing enhancements (e.g. new options, store-specific behavior, parity with other scrapers), check `docs/POSTPONED.md` so we don’t accidentally implement something we’ve deferred.

- Evaluate code changes and recommendations from a pragmatic engineering perspective. We want high quality code with a good velocity. Is it YAGNI? If so, lets us know, and we will decide whether to do it or not.
- Update the CHANGELOG.md as we go, don't cover minuscule changes but anything substantial. Changelogs report only what was implemented; do not reference todo docs (e.g. POSTPONED.md), issue lists, or similar "items to do."

- Remind me to stay on target if I start working on things that aren't pragmatic or moving us forward.